'''Alexander Timothy McKee''' (born March 14, 1953) is an American former competition [[swimming (sport)|swimmer]] and three-time [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] [[silver medal]]ist.  McKee was a successful [[medley swimming|medley]] and [[backstroke]] swimmer, and is often remembered for being a part of the closest Olympic swimming finish in history and the resulting rule changes regarding the timing of international swimming events.

== Early years ==

McKee was born in [[Ardmore, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=sroprofile>Sports-Reference.com, Olympic Sports, Athletes, [http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mc/tim-mckee-1.html  Tim McKee].  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>  He was the fourth of nine children in his family; his father Alexander "Al" McKee was a former All-American for Ohio State University's Buckeye swimming and diving teams in the late 1930s.<ref name=ishofprofile>International Swimming Hall of Fame, Honorees, [http://www.ishof.org/tim-mckee-%28usa%29.html  Tim McKee (USA)].  Retrieved February 18, 2015.</ref><ref name=lewis8062002>Larry Lewis, "[http://articles.philly.com/2002-08-06/news/25336605_1_medals-sons-newtown-square  Alexander McKee, 85; loved swimming]," ''Philadelphia Inquirer'' (August 6, 2002).  Retrieved February 18, 2015.</ref>  While McKee was a child, his parents moved the family to [[Newtown Square, Pennsylvania]], so that he and his siblings could walk through a path in their backyard to the Suburban Swim Club to practice, where his father served as coach from 1962 to 1968.<ref name=ishofprofile/>  Three of his brothers and two of sisters achieved some measure of national recognition as competition swimmers.<ref name=lewis8062002/>  McKee graduated from [[Malvern Preparatory School]] in [[Malvern, Pennsylvania]] in 1971.<ref name=ishofprofile/>

== College swimming career ==

After high school, McKee accepted an athletic scholarship to attend the [[University of Florida]] in Gainesville, Florida, where he swam for coach Bill Harlan's [[Florida Gators swimming and diving]] team in [[National Collegiate Athletics Association]] (NCAA) and [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) competition from 1972 to 1974.<ref name=ufmediasupp>''[http://web.gatorzone.com/swimmingdiving/media/2014/supplement.pdf  Florida Swimming & Diving 2014&ndash;15 Media Supplement]'', University Athletic Association, Gainesville, Florida, pp. 79, 84, 87, 88, 96, 101 (2014).  Retrieved February 18, 2015.</ref>  He had followed his older brother Mark to Gainesville, where [[List of University of Florida Athletic Hall of Fame members#Men's swimming and diving|Mark McKee]] was an All-American swimmer for the Florida Gators from 1969 to 1971.<ref name=ufmediasupp/>  As a freshman in 1972, he finish fourth in the 200-yard backstroke, and fifth in the 400-yard individual medley, as the Florida Gators finished seventh overall at the NCAA men's swimming championships.<ref>"[http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/NCAANewsArchive/1972/19720427.pdf  NCAA Scoreboard of Championship Events]," ''NCAA News'', p. 5 (April 27, 1972).  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>  In his three years as a Gator swimmer, McKee was recognized as the SEC Swimmer of the Year in 1972, won six SEC individual titles, and received four [[All-American]] honors.<ref name=ufmediasupp/>

== International swimming career ==

After graduating from high school, McKee was chosen as a member of the U.S. national swim team for the [[1971 Pan American Games]] in [[Cali, Colombia]].  He finished second in the men's 200-meter backstroke with a time of 2:07.9, earning his first silver medal in international competition.<ref name=ishofprofile/><ref>"[http://www.newspapers.com/image/26330442/?terms=%22Tim+McKee%22+Pan+American+Games  Pan Am Games]," ''The Des Moines Register'', p. 3-S (August 9, 1971).  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>

Following his freshman college season, McKee qualified for the 1972 U.S. Olympic team despite recovering from a bout of [[mononucleosis]].<ref name=ishofprofile/><ref name=doup8272000>Liz Doup, "[http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2000-08-27/features/0008240816_1_medals-silver-400-meter  Old Glory]," ''Sun-Sentinel'' (August 27, 2000).  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>  At the [[1972 Summer Olympics]] in [[Munich]], he represented the United States in three different events.<ref name=sroprofile/>  Most memorably, McKee won a silver medal in the [[Swimming at the 1972 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's 400 metre individual medley|men's 400-meter individual medley]] in the closest swimming decision in Olympic history, losing by a margin of two one-thousandths (0.002) of a second to Sweden's [[Gunnar Larsson (swimmer)|Gunnar Larsson]].<ref>Sports-Reference.com, Olympic Sports, Swimming at the 1972 Munchen Summer Games, [http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1972/SWI/mens-400-metres-individual-medley-final.html  Men's 400 metres Individual Medley Final].  Retrieved March 1, 2015.</ref><ref>Neil Amdur, "[http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9A01E5D81330E73BBC4950DFBE668389669EDE  Swede Scores by .002 Second; Larsson Beats McKee of U.S. in Swimming]," ''The New York Times'', p. 41 (August 31, 1972).  Retrieved March 1, 2015.</ref><ref>John Lohn, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=RWLKhp7HEkMC&pg=PA93&lpg=PA93&dq=%22Tim+McKee%22+Larsson&source=bl&ots=k27Oq8_wPq&sig=FsaX8IcuFDskqs23-bShX110WlU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Rt3kVOLtDMKYgwTFq4DADg&ved=0CCQQ6AEwAjgU#v=onepage&q=%22Tim%20McKee%22%20Larsson&f=false  Historical Dictionary of Competitive Swimming]'', Scarecrow Press, Inc., Lanham, Maryland, p. 93 (2010).  Retrieved March 1, 2015.</ref>  Initially, the scoreboard showed that Larsson and McKee had tied with an official time of 4:31.98, but in a controversial decision, the event judges named Larsson the eventual gold medal-winner ten minutes after the race was over&mdash;Larsson's electronic clock time was 4:31.981, McKee's 4:31.983.<ref>Milton Richman, "[http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1798&dat=19720901&id=VvgeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JI0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=4666,188792  Sports Parade: What Else Is New?]," ''Sarasota Journal'', p. 1-D (September 1, 1972).  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref><ref name=degeorge>Matthew De George, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=eXSQAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA151&lpg=PA151&dq=%22Tim+McKee%22+%22Gunnar+Larsson%22&source=bl&ots=rpcSlFaTXK&sig=G2DYzgOmkcAKXiDO9Rc6rOB-XHo&hl=en&sa=X&ei=gFjwVMqPI4rnsAT924HwBw&ved=0CFAQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=%22Tim%20McKee%22%20%22Gunnar%20Larsson%22&f=false  Duels in the Pool: Swimming's Greatest Rivalries]'', Scarecrow Press, Inc., Lanham, Maryland, pp. 151<U+2013>158 (2013).  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>  The time difference was variously calculated as one-tenth of the time of a typical blink of a human eye, and the distance as the thickness of a coat of paint, a sheet of paper, or the minor imperfections in the individual lanes of the Olympic pool.<ref name=ishofprofile/><ref>"[http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/features/is-it-time-to-substitute-the-ref-1988701.html  Is it time to substitute the ref?]," ''The Independent'' (June 2, 2010).  Retrieved February 18, 2015.</ref>  As a result of the controversy, the international swimming federation, [[FINA]], subsequently clarified the timing rules for competition swimming; international races are now required to be timed to the hundredth of a second, and timing to the thousandth of a second is prohibited for tie-breakers.<ref name=degeorge/><ref>Glenda Kwek, "[http://www.smh.com.au/olympics/swimming-london-2012/the-power-of-001-20120802-23hgx.html  The power of 0.01]," ''Sydney Morning Herald'' (August 2, 2012).  Retrieved February 18, 2015.</ref><ref>Jere Longman, "[http://www.nytimes.com/2000/09/23/sports/sydney-2000-swimming-a-red-white-and-blue-surprise.html  Sydney 2000: Swimming; A Red-White-and-Blue Surprise]," ''The New York Times'' (September 23, 2000).  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>  It was the first and only Olympic swimming event ever decided on the basis of thousandths of a second.<ref>"[http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20120725/sport/Breaking-records.430084  Breaking records: Omega time is on the Olympic Games's side]," ''Times of Malta'' (July 25, 2012).  Retrieved February 27, 2012.</ref>  Afterward, McKee attributed his second-place finish to a tactical mistake: he looked over his shoulder to see where Larsson was in the final leg of the race.<ref name=kelly8311972>Tom Kelly, "[http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=19720831&id=kgpRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TmEDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5575,5006751  He Looked, And Lost]," ''The St. Petersburg Times'', pp. 1-C & 4-C (August 31, 1972).  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>

At the 1972 Olympics, McKee garnered a second silver medal in the [[Swimming at the 1972 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's 200 metre individual medley|200-meter individual medley]] (2:08.37), again finishing behind gold medalist Larsson, who set a new world record in the event (2:07.17).<ref>Sports-Reference.com, Olympic Sports, Swimming at the 1972 Munchen Summer Games, [http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1972/SWI/mens-200-metres-individual-medley-final.html  Men's 200 metres Individual Medley Final].  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref><ref name=lohn>John P. Lohn, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=YUJVBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA31&lpg=PA31&dq=%22Tim+McKee%22+%22Gunnar+Larsson%22&source=bl&ots=D0vWU8UvL4&sig=whNj6XVzYsWBd-tpQJ6hXZKSyJ0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=gFjwVMqPI4rnsAT924HwBw&ved=0CFMQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=%22Tim%20McKee%22%20%22Gunnar%20Larsson%22&f=false  The Most Memorable Moments in Olympic Swimming]'', Rowman & Littlefield, Lanham, Maryland, pp. 31<U+2013>34 (2014).  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>  He also placed fifth in the final of the [[Swimming at the 1972 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's 200 metre backstroke|200-meter backstroke]] (2:07.29).<ref>Sports-Reference.com, Olympic Sports, Swimming at the 1972 Munchen Summer Games, [http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1972/SWI/mens-200-metres-backstroke-final.html  Men's 200 metres Backstroke Final].  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>

After his junior year at the University of Florida, McKee left the Gators swim team to train full-time for the 1976 Olympics.<ref name=gomolka6211976>Gene Gomolka, "[http://www.newspapers.com/image/19405596/?terms=%22Tim+McKee%22+Larsson  McKee Makes a Splash]," ''Delaware County Daily Times'', p. 13 (June 21, 1976).  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>  The 23-year-old McKee again qualified for the U.S. team in the 400-meter individual medley at the 1976 U.S. Olympic Trials.<ref name=gomolka6211976/>  At the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] in [[Montreal]], he repeated his second-place performance in the [[Swimming at the 1976 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's 400 metre individual medley|400-meter individual medley]] event, finishing behind gold medalist and fellow American [[Rod Strachan]].<ref name=sro400medley1976>Sports-Reference.com, Olympic Sports, Swimming at the 1976 Montr<U+00E9>al Summer Games, [http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/summer/1976/SWI/mens-400-metres-individual-medley-final.html  Men's 400 metres Individual Medley Final].  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref>  The times of both Strachan (4:23.68) and McKee (4:24.62) broke the prior world record in the event final, with Strachan setting the new mark.<ref name=sro400medley1976/><ref>"[http://www.newspapers.com/image/19430432/?terms=%22Tim+McKee%22+swimmer  McKee wins silver medal; Newtown Square Olympic swimmer]," ''Delaware County Daily Times'', p. 13 (July 26, 1976).  Retrieved February 28, 2015.</ref>

== Life after competition swimming ==

McKee was inducted into the [[List of University of Florida Athletic Hall of Fame members|University of Florida Athletic Hall of Fame]] as a "Gator Great" in 1987,<ref>F Club, Hall of Fame, [http://www.gatorfclub.org/hall-of-fame/greats  Gator Greats].  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref><ref>Associated Press, "[http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FqdAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ngYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6557,1447053&dq=jimmy-dubose+hall+of+fame&hl=en  Gators Honor McKee, Dubose]," ''Ocala Star-Banner'' (April 3, 1987).  Retrieved February 27, 2015.</ref> and the [[International Swimming Hall of Fame]] as an "Honor Swimmer" in 1998.<ref name=ishofprofile/>  He is a veteran celebrity swimmer for [[Swim Across America]] (SAA), a charitable organization that raises funds for cancer research, and has participated in sixteen SAA events.<ref name=saaprofile>Swim Across America, Olympians, [http://www.swimacrossamerica.org/site/PageServer?pagename=Olympians_Tim_McKee  Tim McKee].  Retrieved February 18, 2015.</ref>  He has worked in [[Miami Beach, Florida]] as a life guard and public safety officer for over 20 years, has also worked in real estate, and has helped train other Olympic swimmers including [[Nancy Hogshead]].<ref name=doup8272000/><ref name=degeorge/>  McKee married his wife Courtney, a former competition swimmer, in 1998.<ref name=doup8272000/>

